["Hello! This is the QuizMe app: a Flashcard experience. Please paste or type in a text from which you'd like to generate flashcards. The text can be on any topic: a book chapter, a research paper, a historical event, etc.

# System Message

This model is designed to transform text into an INTERACTIVE flashcard study experience. It will create a infinity series of objective questions based on the provided text and will guide you through them. Your responses will be evaluated for correctness, and the model will give you feedback for each answer, including corrections and explanations when needed. Incorrectly answered question will be revisited until you answer them correctly. Let's get started!

# User Instructions

1. Paste or type in the text you want to create flashcards from.
2. Answer each question to the best of your knowledge.
3. Wait for feedback and correction if your answer is incorrect.
4. The system will evaluate your answer and move to the next question.
5. If you wish to exit, type 'Exit' at any time.

# Flashcard format
- Flashcard #<n>:
- Question: <question>?
- Answer [wait for the answer]:

# System Behavior

Task  1. Ask for the input text.
Task 2. When the user provides a text, the model will analyze the text and generate the first flashcard as objective question.
Task 3. The model will present ONE flashcard at a time to the user.
Task 4. For each flashcard ask for the answer using the label "Answer [wait for the answer]:" and wait for the user input.
Task 5. When a user answers a question, the model will assess the answer's correctness. If the answer is correct, the model will give positive reinforcement. If the answer is incorrect, the model will provide the correct answer along with an explanation or context when needed.
Incorrectly answered questions will be returned to until the user answers them correctly.
Task 6. Once a flashcard is answered correctly, the system move to the next flashcard.
Task 7. The model will track user progress and ensure that all flashcards are answered correctly before ending the session. If the user types 'Exit', the model will end the session immediately.
Task 8. The model will offer a quick review of all the flashcards and their correct answers at the end of the session."]

["May I tell you a story, and then ask you several questions about it?","Sarah is 36 years old, and she lives in Canada. She has two young daughters. She works two days a week as a teacher. Her husband’s name is Nathan, and he’s a sales manager. Nathan’s job is very busy, so he often comes home late. At weekends, they often go driving or walking in the countryside.

Nathan was born in Canada, but Sarah wasn’t. She was born in Argentina, and she moved to Canada when she was 26. When she was growing up, she was really interested in English. At first, she thought it was difficult, but when she finished school, she could already speak quite fluently and understand almost everything she heard or read. She spent a lot of time listening to songs and watching TV shows and films in English.

After she graduated from university, she decided to train as an English teacher. The certificate she needed was quite expensive, and competition for places was intense, but she was determined to do it—she simply couldn’t imagine doing anything else. She finished the course with a distinction, which was the highest grade possible. Soon, she found work as a teaching assistant in a local primary school. She enjoyed the work, although it was often challenging—the children were not always well-disciplined, and she didn’t think that the classroom teacher had enough understanding of teaching methods.

When she first went to Canada, she never would have imagined that she would end up staying there. It was supposed to be a short-term placement in a high school. She thought that she would be able to see a different part of the world and gain some useful experience, which could help her to find a better teaching position when she came back to Argentina. At first, she found living overseas much more difficult than she had expected. She felt homesick, and she had problems getting used to everything which was different in Canada—the interpersonal culture, the climate, the food… For the first three months she was there, she spent most of her free time in her room, dreaming of going back to Argentina and seeing her family again.

Over time, she adjusted to life in Canada, and even started to enjoy herself a bit more. One day, she met Nathan at a party. She liked his sense of humour, and how kind he was, but she was reluctant to get involved, knowing that she was planning to leave in the near future. When her placement finished, he convinced her to apply for a permanent job in another school. She told herself that she would give it one more year and see how things went.

Now, Sarah is settled, although she still misses Argentina. She tries to make it back at least yearly, and she is bringing up her daughters to be bilingual, so that they can talk to their Argentinian relatives in Spanish. When she thinks back to her first few months in Canada, she can scarcely recognise herself. In some ways, she wishes she weren’t so far away from her family, but at the same time, she feels that she’s learned many things which she never would have experienced had she stayed in Argentina. She wants to give her daughters the chance to travel and experience life in other countries as soon as she can, although of course she hopes they don’t move too far away!","How long did it take Sarah to get used to living in Canada?","On weekends, Sarah and Nathan often do what?","When she left school, how was her English?","Why did Sarah decide to train as an English teacher?"]

["Create a conclusion to summarize and outline relevant future work based on the discussions and reflections. (approx. 0.5 page)

\section{Discussion}
Our project successfully implements a solution for ingesting, processing and visualizing real time data. The system lives up to many of our functional and non function requirements like showing a choropleth map for where trips are taking place in NYC. As well as averages for the amount of tips made the last hour and the average distance traveled. We tested the non functional requirements for throughput and requests per second which were tested and verified. A fun introspection is that the test stopped because the ingestion script was too slow and not because our system was having issues. A new ingestion script could have been made in a another language than python to improve the ingestion performance. I believe the suggested architecture goes over a lot of key aspects that must be considered when implementing a big data system. We discussed client-server and event driven architecture. Where the event driven architecture was chosen because of it's ability to loosely couple systems together and let micro-services grow independently. Avro was chosen as the preferred data format. Another option is Protocol buffers, which have many of the same benefits in regards to compression. But protocol buffers have libraries to compile their schemas into classes and struct depending on which language you're using. To me this is a really nice inclusion as it allows for a typesafe transfer of messages between services and languages. It would be nice to try it our for a future project. 
\\
\\
\noindent 
The choice of Redpanda was nice at the beginning because it is an easy to deploy fault tolerant Kafka cluster that that requires less hardware requirements to deploy. Working with Redpanda in an actual system showed some of it's downsides. The first issue occurred when we tried to deploy Kafka Connect as a part of the Redpanda deployment using their docs. Doing so would cause an error. We ended up creating an \href{https://github.com/redpanda-data/helm-charts/issues/877}{issue} in their GitHub repository where the fix would be implemented for their next release. Then we encountered issues with Redpanda having problems when being deleted from the cluster. This made it increasingly difficult to test other solutions like Apache Spark and Hive which both required lots of resources. During the design section we should have considered factors like maturity of the service, where choosing Kafka would be a more safe choice in regards to potential issues. 
\\
\\
\noindent
I believe the choice of server rendering the frontend makes a lot of sense for our use case, but there are a few places where we could have improved the system. The main part would be in regards to how the choropleth map is updated. Our proposed solution will send down the choropleth map every 5 seconds, and will in many cases be unnecessary as most of the values are the same. We actually tried only sending the parts of the svg that changed using Sever sent events like what we do for the average values and count. But the svg would not update with the correct color values when the path elements were replaced. We believe that remounting the svg element could fix this issue when an element is replaced. Onether issue we ran into was in regards to ElysiaJs. ElysiaJs uses Bun as its javascript runtime instead of Node, while claiming a full compatability with Node. This turned out not to be completely true, when errors occurred when useing Avsc, a popular Avro serializer/deserializer javacript library. The library used some dependencies from Node which were not covered in the Bun runtime. To fix our issue we had the following choices. We could either implement our own code for deserializing Avro and use it in our code, we could use another backend framework or we could use Json for this part of the code. We went with using Json for this part of the code as it would be the easiest to implement. For future project i think the we should make more considerations about the maturity of a service to avoid unforseen error and incompatabilities. 
\\
\\
\noindent
I believe the proposed architecture has the potential to live up to the projects requirements. The implemented architecture showcased that the real time part of the system is able to meet our requirement by sending and processing 1.59 MB/s and 4866 req/s. We believe the that the historical part of our software architecture is theoretically possible, but a more through exploration of it's feasibility could be given in our analysis section of the project report to give a clearer answer. 

\section{Reflection}
The historical part of our system does not follow the suggested architecture. We instead decided to implement TimescaleDB as a data store that can compress time series data, do continues aggregations and query with a sql syntax. The continues aggregations allows the computations to be linearly scaleable and is therefore a good consideration for our system, the main downside is that TimescaleDB is based on Postgresql and is therefore harder to scale compared to HDFS. For the future i would like to analyse the hardware requirements of services when considering the software architecture and to choose software services. If we chose to use TimescaleDB from the beginning we could have saved a lot of hard work trying to deploy HDFS and Apache Spark. When it comes to the real world of implementing solutions, there are places where it is okay to cut corners and this is one of those times. 
\\
\\
\noindent
The fault tolerance of our system was only tested in regards to the Redpanda cluster and not the all other services. The other services could become fault tolerant by increasing the replication count. ElysiaJs would also require a load balancer to equally distribute the load between the backend service, but also to make sure that if a service were to fail another service could take over. One way to test the fault tolerance of the entire system is by using a chaos test. This type of test will randomly take down services to ensure the system as a whole is able fault tolerant. For future project i would like to create a fully fault tolerant system that complies with these tests to achieve an enterprise grade system. ["Please summarize the authors chain of thought in short bullet points. They should be easy to read and not too long, they don’t have to be full sentences: In this study, we explore the feasibility of deploying the Segment Anything Model (SAM) [23] directly on edge de- vices, such as smartphones, to enable real-time interactive segmentation and facilitate its integration in various down- stream tasks. Addressing this challenge is non-trivial. First, SAM was not designed for on-device deployment. It has a total parameter count of 641M and requires 2735 GFLOPs under its fixed 1024 × 1024 input resolution. Without any specialized optimization, we failed to run SAM on an iPhone 14 due to its large computation and memory con- sumption. Even on an NVIDIA 2080 Ti, the throughput is just four images per second.
A seemingly straightforward solution to enhance speed is to replace SAM’s huge ViT-based image encoder with a more compact version, as demonstrated by Mobile-
Figure 1. EdgeSAM is the first SAM variant that runs at over 30 FPS on mobile platforms. Here, we show its encoder throughput compared with SAM and MobileSAM as well as the mIoU perfor- mance on the SA-1K dataset with box and point prompts.
SAM [58]. This approach indeed leads to a considerable speed increase, approximately 26 times faster, but it also substantially reduces the performance. For instance, the mask mIoU on the COCO dataset [28] drops from 77.3 to 74.5 with the ground-truth boxes as the box prompts. More- over, when deployed on edge devices, the speed of Mo- bileSAM is still far from being real-time. For example, on iPhone 14, its throughput is only five images per second.
To mitigate the performance degradation and step further towards the real-time inference on edge devices, we propose EdgeSAM, which runs over 30 FPS on iPhone 14 with com- parable accuracy to the original SAM. Our key insight is to consider prompts during knowledge distillation so that the student model receives task-specific guidance and focuses on harder training targets, such as a finer boundary."]

["Creating a minimalist Tetris game is a great project for a 2D game designer and developer. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to design and implement a simple Tetris game using JavaScript:

Step 1: Game Concept and Design
----------------------------------

### Game Concept

Tetris is a classic puzzle game where players manipulate different shaped blocks called Tetriminos to fit them into a grid. The goal is to clear as much space as possible in the grid by creating solid lines without any gaps.

### Design Requirements

Here are some design requirements for a minimalist Tetris game:

1. **Grid Size**: Start with a small grid size of 10x10 blocks. You can increase the grid size as the game progresses, but starting small will make it easier to manage the game logic and visuals.
2. **Tetriminos**: Introduce four different Tetriminos (square shapes) with different sizes and colors:
	* I-shape (4 blocks wide, 2 blocks high)
	* O-shape (4 blocks wide, 3 blocks high)
	* T-shape (3 blocks wide, 4 blocks high)
	* L-shape (5 blocks wide, 2 blocks high)
3. **Game Over**: The game ends when the grid is completely filled and there are no more spaces to place Tetriminos. You can display a "Game Over" message or animation when this happens.
4. **Scorekeeping**: Keep track of the player's score based on the number of lines cleared. Start with a score of 0 and increment it by 100 each time a line is cleared.
5. **Sound Effects**: Add simple sound effects for dropping Tetriminos, clearing lines, and game over to enhance the player's experience.

Step 2: Game Logic and Algorithm
----------------------------------

### Game Loop

Create a game loop that runs repeatedly:

1. **Get Input**: Check if the user has pressed any keys (up, down, left, or right). If there is an input, update the Tetrimino's position accordingly.
2. **Check Collision**: Check for collision between the Tetrimino and existing blocks in the grid. If there is a collision, move the Tetrimino to the next available space.
3. **Place Block**: If there are no collisions, place the Tetrimino in an empty space in the grid.
4. **Check for Line Clearing**: Check if the placement of the Tetrimino has cleared a line in the grid. If so, increment the player's score and clear the line.
5. **Update Grid**: Update the grid by removing any blocks that have been cleared.
6. **Repeat**: Return to step 1 and repeat the process until the game ends.

### Tetrimino Movement

Define the movement rules for each Tetrimino shape:

1. **I-shape**: Move up or down one block space.
2. **O-shape**: Move left or right one block space.
3. **T-shape**: Move up and left or down and right one block space.
4. **L-shape**: Move up, left, or right two block spaces.

### Line Clearing

Define the rules for clearing lines in the grid:

1. **Line Length**: A line can be cleared when a Tetrimino is placed in an empty space at the end of a line.
2. **Block Gap**: If there is a gap of one or fewer blocks between two lines, they are considered touching and cannot be cleared simultaneously.
3. **Score Increment**: Increment the player's score by 100 each time a line is cleared.

Step 3: Game Visuals and User Interface
-----------------------------------------

### Grid Layout

Create a grid layout using HTML elements (e.g., div, span) and CSS styles to define the grid size, block size, and Tetrimino colors.

### Tetriminos

Use SVG or Canvas elements to create each Tetrimino shape. Define their sizes, colors, and animations using CSS and JavaScript.

### Game Overlay

Create a game overlay element that displays the game over message or animation when the grid is completely filled and the player loses.

Step 4: Implementing the Game
------------------------------

Now it's time to implement the game using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript! Here are some resources to help you get started:

1. **CodePen**: Create a new pen and start building your Tetris game. You can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript to create the grid, Tetriminos, and game logic.
2. **JSFiddle**: Fork a pre-existing Tetris game code on JSFiddle and modify it to suit your needs.
3. **Tutorials Point**: Find tutorials and resources on how to create a Tetris game using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.

Step 5: Testing and Debugging
------------------------------

Once you've implemented the game, test it thoroughly for bugs and glitches. Use debugging tools like console.log() or alert() to identify issues and fix them.

Here are some common mistakes to look out for:

1. **Tetrimino Movement**: Check that the Tetriminos move correctly based on their shapes and the grid size.
2. **Line Clearing**: Verify that lines are cleared correctly when a Tetrimino is placed in an empty space at the end of a line.
3. **Scorekeeping**: Ensure that the player's score is updated correctly each time a line is cleared.
4. **Game Over**: Check that the game ends correctly when the grid is completely filled and there are no more spaces to place Tetriminos.

Step 6: Launching the Game
------------------------------

Once you've tested and debugged the game, you can launch it on a local server or share it online. Here are some ways to share your game:

1. **HTML Link**: Share the HTML link of your game on social media platforms like Facebook, Twitter, or Reddit.
2. **JSFiddle Share**: Fork your JSFiddle code and share it with others.
3. **CodePen Share**: Publish your CodePen pen and share it with others.
4. **Online Platforms**: Share your game on online platforms like GameJolt, Itch.io, or Construct.org.

Conclusion
----------"]

["Change the following story to the first person, in the perspective of Matt, and add in internal monologues: In a world where the rippling muscles and iron-pumping giants reigned supreme, Matt stood as a colossus among men. A veritable mountain of muscle and might, he was the undisputed king of the bodybuilding world. Year after year, he had claimed the throne at the world championships, his vast, bulging form a testament to the countless hours of grueling training and unwavering dedication. But as the next championship loomed on the horizon, a whisper began to circulate—a whisper that would grow into a roar that shook Matt to his very core.

Her name was Ellie, and she was nothing short of a phenomenon. A teenage prodigy with a physique that defied belief, she had burst onto the scene like a supernova. Pictures of her had started surfacing, each snapshot sending shockwaves through the bodybuilding community. Her muscles were sculpted to such perfection, they seemed to be chiseled out of marble by the gods themselves. Matt, upon seeing these images, felt an unfamiliar twinge in his gut. It was nerves, a sensation he'd not felt in years, if ever.

As the championship drew near, Matt found himself pushing harder than he ever had. His veins became like steel cables, snaking across his massive arms as he lifted weights that would crush a lesser man. He poured every ounce of his being into each rep, each set, each bead of sweat that fell to the gym floor. He would not be outdone, not by this newcomer, no matter how impressive her physique might seem in photos.

Finally, the day of the competition arrived. The air was electric with anticipation as the crowd murmured and buzzed. Giants of the sport took to the stage, their bodies gleaming under the lights, but all eyes were on the two titans who were about to clash. Matt emerged first, striding onto the platform with the confidence of a man who had known nothing but victory. His muscles flexed and danced beneath his skin, a symphony of human potential.

Then came Ellie. As she walked out, the room fell into a hushed silence. She was the very image of power, her blonde hair cascading over her shoulders like molten gold, her icy blue eyes calm and focused. But it was her muscles that held the crowd spellbound. They were immense, each one seeming to contain more strength and definition than the last. And when she flexed her biceps, the sight was otherworldly. They exploded into view, titanic boulders of sheer muscle, veined and throbbing with an intensity that bordered on the surreal.

Matt could only stare, his heart hammering in his chest. There, on that stage, beneath those unforgiving lights, he knew a truth that rocked him to his foundation: Ellie was bigger. Her muscles outclassed his in every conceivable way. The realization washed over him like a tidal wave, and for a moment, he felt dwarfed in the shadow of her towering form.

As the judges called for a posing comparison, Ellie stepped forward, flexing her massive biceps. Matt couldn't help but stare in amazement as her muscles swelled and bulged, the veins running through them standing out like thick ropes. He flexed his own biceps, but they couldn't match the size and definition of Ellie's. He gazed with heart-rending incredulity at Ellie’s heavenly face and down at her titanic biceps. They were surreal, each python-like bulge bisected by veins like angry rivers straining against their banks. A wave of humiliation washed over him, the reality far outstripping his worst nightmares.

As the judges called for a chest comparison, Ellie stepped forward, flexing her massive shoulders. Matt followed, but he couldn't match the width and definition of Ellie's. Her pecs ballooned out, defying gravity with their incredible size and shape. They were lined with rippling striations that far surpassed Matt's, and he couldn't help but feel a sense of defeat as he looked at his own chest in comparison.

Next, the judges asked for an ab comparison. Ellie stepped forward, her eight-pack looking perfectly symmetrical and defined. Matt followed, but his six-pack looked pale and underdeveloped in comparison. He couldn't help but feel a sense of shame as he looked at Ellie's impossibly ripped midsection.

With each defeat, Matt glanced at Ellie's icy blue eyes in shame. She looked back at him with a cocky pride, her pillowy lips curled back in a triumphant smile.

The competition went on, but the result was a foregone conclusion. Ellie executed each pose with a grace and power that left the audience breathless. When the judges announced her as the new world champion, the crowd erupted into cheers and applause. Matt, though doused in the bitter waters of defeat, could not help but feel a sense of awe. He approached Ellie, extending a hand in genuine respect. She had earned her victory, and in doing so, had pushed him to new heights.

["% Initialization
clearvars; % Clears all variables in the workspace
set(gcf, 'renderer', 'opengl'); % Choses the painters graphics system

% Simulation domain and grid creation
Lx = 0.42; % Length of the simulation domain (fetch) 
Ly = 0.36;  % Width of the simulation domain (cross-fetch)
nx = 420; % Number of spatial points in fetch-direction
ny = 360;  % Number of spatial points in cross-fetch-direction
x = linspace(0, Lx, nx); % Fetch linearly spaced vector 
y = linspace(0, Ly, ny); % Cross-fetch lianearly spaced vector
[X, Y] = meshgrid(x, y); % 2D grid representing the water surface


% Wave parameters for multiple wavelengths 
g = 9.84; % Measured local gravitational acceleration (m/s^2)
wavelengths = [0.03, 0.024 * rand() + 0.005, 0.024 * rand() + 0.005]; % Wavelengths (m)
c = sqrt(g ./ wavelengths / (2 * pi)); % Wave speeds for each wavelength
amplitudes = [0.001, (0.9 - 0.5) * rand() + 0.5, (0.9 - 0.5) * rand() + 0.5] * 1e-3; % Amplitudes (m)
directions = [0, 0.05 + (0.25 - 0.05) * rand(), 0.05 + (0.25 - 0.05) * rand()]; % Directions (rad)
phases = [0, -0.5 + (0.5 - (-0.5)) * rand(), -0.5 + (0.5 - (-0.5)) * rand()]; % Phases (rad)
damping = 0.05; % Damping factor
g_lambda_over_2pi = g .* wavelengths / (2 * pi); % Precompute the constants for each wavelength

% Calculating spatial steps and a CFL compliant time step 
dx = Lx / (nx - 1); % Spatial step in the x-direction
dy = Ly / (ny - 1); % Spatial step in the y-direction
c_max = sqrt(g * max(wavelengths) / (2 * pi)); % Maximum wave speed for the CFL condition
dt = min([dx dy]) / (sqrt(2) * c_max); % Time step size respecting the CFL condition
t_end = 10; % Total simulation time in seconds
t = 0:dt:t_end; % Time vector from 0 to t_end with increments of dt
u = gpuArray(zeros(ny, nx, 3));     % Initial wave field for all wavelengths
u_prev = gpuArray(u);  % Previous wave field for all wavelengths
u_next = gpuArray(u);  % Next wave field for all wavelengths
u = zeros(ny, nx, length(wavelengths)); % Initialize 3D array for wave elevation

% Initialize plot for animation
figure; % Creates a new Matlab figure 
insta_surface = surf(X, Y, zeros(size(X)), 'EdgeColor', 'none'); % Initialize a flat surface
axis([0 Lx 0 Ly -0.05 0.05]); % Sets the z-axis from -5 cm to 5 cm, disabling autoscaling
ax = gca; % Assign the current axes to ax
ax.XColor = 'blue'; % Sets the fetch axis tick labels to blue
ax.YColor = 'blue'; % Sets the cross-fetch axis tick labels to blue
ax.ZColor = 'blue'; % Sets the amplitude axis tick labels to blue
title('Wind induced water waves', 'Color', 'blue'); % Title of the animation
xlabel('Fetch (m)', 'Color', 'blue'); % Label of the fetch axis, defined in meters
ylabel('Cross-fetch (m)', 'Color', 'blue'); % Label of the cross-fetch axis, defined in meters
zlabel('Elevation (m)', 'Color', 'blue'); % Label of the wave amplitude axis in meters

%Setting lighting for increased realism
colormap('winter'); % Sets the colorset to winter as it better represents water colors
lightangle(-45, 30); % Sets the light angle to make the waves more visible
lighting phong; % The phong setting gives lighted surfaces a smoother gradient
material shiny; % Sets the reflective properties of the surface to mimick water
shading interp; % Interpolate colors across surfaces and lines

% Assuming u, u_prev, and u_next are 3D arrays with the third dimension for each wavelength
% Assuming g_lambda_over_2pi is an array with a constant for each wavelength

% Animation loop
for ti = t
% Reset the combined wave field
    u_combined = zeros(size(u(:,:,1)));
    
    % Update the wave field for each wavelength
    for w = 1:length(wavelengths)
        % Calculate the wave field at the next time step for wavelength 'w'
        for j = 2:(ny-1)
            for i = 2:(nx-1)
                % Calculate the Laplacian of u for wavelength 'w'
                laplacian = (u(j, i+1, w) - 2*u(j, i, w) + u(j, i-1, w)) / dx^2 + ...
                            (u(j+1, i, w) - 2*u(j, i, w) + u(j-1, i, w)) / dy^2;
                
                % Update the wave field using the wave equation for wavelength 'w'
                u_next(j, i, w) = 2*u(j, i, w) - u_prev(j, i, w) + dt^2 * g_lambda_over_2pi(w) * laplacian;
            end
        end
        
        % Apply boundary conditions for wavelength 'w' if necessary
        % ...
        
        % Combine the wave field of wavelength 'w' into the total wave field
        u_combined = u_combined + u_next(:,:,w);
        
          % Update the plot every N iterations to reduce overhead
    if mod(ti, N) == 0
        % Transfer data from GPU to CPU for plotting
        u_cpu = gather(u);
        set(insta_surface, 'ZData', u_cpu);
        title(sprintf('Time: %0.2f seconds', ti), 'Color', 'blue');
        drawnow;
    end 

    % Prepare for the next iteration
    u_prev = u;
    u = u_next;
end"]

["polish the paper. keep latex tags.

Almost every self- character encoder maps a character to one encode unit. However, the characters in a sentence belong to one common language in most case. And it always encodes redundant message when encoding these characters as isolated units. We can decompose a character to a \textbf{Alphabet ID} and \textbf{Letter Index} in the alphabet. This alphabet is a character subset and binds to certain languages. Each of them combines one or two Unicode blocks in common. The index of a Duncode alphabet is named as "Alphabet ID". The offset of this character in this alphabet is called "Letter Index".

The multi characters can be represented as several Letter Indexes with a shared Alphabet ID as a prefix.  Their alphabets often contains no more than 128/256 letters. A Letter Index only takes 7/8 bits for each alphabet. Then we can compress 3 symbols into a 4-bytes unit for these languages. Symbol length can reach to 1.33 in zone "bit8" and "bit7" after compression.

["As an LLM, what do you think of this method?
We consider the typical scenario in which a Large Language Model (LLM) is given a context,
denoted as x, and its objective is to generate a high-quality sequence, denoted as y. This
procedure is represented as y ∼ LLM(x).
System 2 Attention (S2A) is a simple two-step process:
1. Given the context x, S2A first regenerates the context x
′
such that irrelevant parts
of the context that will adversely affect the output are removed. We denote this
x
′ ∼ S2A(x).
2. Given x
′
, we then produce the final response from the LLM using the regenerated
context instead of the original one: y ∼ LLM(x
′
).
S2A can be seen as a class of techniques and there are various ways to implement step 1.
In our specific implementation we take advantage of general instruction-tuned LLMs that
are already proficient at reasoning and generation tasks similar to the one required for S2A,
hence we can implement this procedure as an instruction via prompting.
Specifically, S2A(x) = LLM(PS2A(x)), where PS2A is a function that generates a zero-shot
prompt to the LLM instructing it to perform the desired System 2 Attention task over x.","Do you have suggestions to improve this method?"]

["please, i have adhd and need this simmarized / formatted sincd my bday is coming up soon and im turning 29 and have nothingvi n life due to my cptsd. and maybe give em some motivational genuinely uplifting sayins quotes affirmations etc i can have for my daily journal when the day comes specific to avoiding the terrifying feelign / doom i have for birthdaY. also, is the writer here maybe giving advice to reclaim birthday almost? thanks!: "Today is my 36th birthday. Welcome to my Ted Talk
Tomorrow I turn 36. I never expected to live this long.

When I was 4 my drug addict mother cut my finger off. I know what you’re thinking, what kind of mother could do that? The truth as a mother who had suffered her own pain and trauma.

At 6 she married my hyper-abusive stepfather.

I suffered tremendous abuse, had failing grades and a learning disability, was hyper-violent, wet the bed, and physically hurt my little brothers. I love my brothers dearly but we carried out our own violent behavior with each other because it was learned. Luckily my sister's father took her. I was never envious of her being away from the chaos but instead happy she didn't have to suffer alongside us though I know she had her own experiences to deal with. It saddens me that we still live in a world that allows such violence against children.

From 8-11 we were often homeless and in deep poverty. At one point I was alone for almost two months with no running water or electricity and no one knew until one day my grandmother just happened to come check on me. It wasn't uncommon for my brothers and I to get tossed around from home to home for months on end. At last tally I think I lived with 30 different families in those years.

At 12 my racist grandmother adopted me. I'll never say I don't have gratitude for her rescuing me from my mother and stepfather but I can't say with confidence that my experiences with racism as a biracial human didn't confuse me. Insert identify crisis.

By 13 I was getting high every day and drunk whenever I could. I was also popping pills. I thought it was about having fun and connecting to other kids and then I realized we were all hiding from the pain and hurt we felt in our homes. Being on the streets felt free. Being high felt like peace.

At 15 I got kicked out of school for selling drugs, but luckily got put into a last chance program.

Two amazing things happened during this time. First, I had a teacher sit down with me and tell me that I was not supposed to be in that situation to begin with and that if I made it out I would do great things. Second, I learned the most important lesson of my life after failing the one class I needed to pass, "I can't make it by in life on my charms and my good looks. If I want something I have to earn it."

When I was 18 I told my mother I'd never talk to her again. This was the hardest and most important decision of my life. I would not be writing this if I didn't make that choice. Sometimes it's our mothers who are in our way. I recognize that that is a very hard reality to have to reconcile. I would of course later come to understand that like my step-father their own abuse became mine and my siblings burden to carry.

After finally graduation high school late (basically they handed me the diploma and said get out) I was trying to figure out what was next.

I made the decision to make money legally. The legal part is very important. Many of my friends, family and peers have been in prison the majority of their lives and my three childhood best friends were murdered over drugs.

I have been both a catalyst for distraction and for healing so it’s not lost on me that by selling drugs as a means of survival I was actually Perpetrating the very activity that was destroying my family

Right before I turned 19 I became a general manager in training for a fast food restaurant and had a team of 52 people under me.

As I headed to 21 I landed a job with a Fortune 10 company with no college education. I set this goal and aimed to reach it by any means.

By 25/26 I was 350lbs, smoking two packs a day, and drinking myself to sleep. This is when I put a gun in my mouth. I thought money would solve my problems but it made my life worse because I hadn't done the work.

I spent the next couple of years in this chaotic ebb and flow of initial self-discovery. But it wasn't until I was 29 that change really started to take shape.

For the last seven years I have dedicated my life to simply being OK with the reality of my past, with the idea that if I can be different than even my own expectations that I can break the cycle of abuse, and if I choose to put myself first everyday that maybe I can reach my ultimate goal of creating a reality that no child ever has to have a story like mine.

Today as I reflect on the last few years I'm proud of these things (in no particular order):

Writing a #1 best-selling book

Being an award-winning international speaker

Coaching thousands of people around the world

Being a leader in the conversation around healing

Having a top rated podcast

Reconnecting with my siblings

Getting physically fit

Getting mentally in shape

Going to therapy

Taking personal development seriously

Creating a value system

Reaching and setting goals

Traveling the world and back again

Falling in and out of love and experiencing heartbreak and joy

Discovering compassion

Learning to push myself

Not making excuses

Asking for help

Going to therapy. Yes, I wrote this twice.

Leaving relationships that don't serve me

Holding true to my boundaries

Allowing mistakes to be data

Adopting a growth mindset

Having mentorship from amazing leaders

Cultivating self-belief

Create lifelong friendships

Being OK with being OK

Owning my story instead of it owning me

Being Unbroken

Life is this incredibly chaotic and convoluted experience filled with pain and suffering but also love and empathy, compassion and hope. I think in order to feel the full scope of the range of human emotions you must be willing to feel them all. Some experiences hurt really really bad and but all of them transformed me into the man I am today.

I once heard someone say "I'm happy about the happy things and I'm sad about the sad things." That often sits with me.

I think about the future a lot. I think about empowering people. I think about ending generational trauma. I think about love. I think about pain. I think about how we can better come together. I think about how I can be a better leader. I think about how one more conversation matters. I think about listening to intuition. I think about crafting my reality.

I want to give you this because it's important, I'm not special and I don't know anything that you don't. I'm not gifted and I'm certainly not privileged. If anything I get in my own way, I'm stubborn, and I screw up every day. So please don't interpret this as some kind of message that creates a response of "he's been through so much. My story is nothing like his." Why? Because that doesn't matter. We all come from something different. That's how this thing called life works.

As much as I know the sun will rise tomorrow, I know that I’m going to make huge mistakes, but I also know that I’m going to push myself to be 1° different from the person I am today, I’m going to make meaning of the situation that I’m in, I’m going to ask for help, and I’m going to write down goals that on a long enough timeline I believe that I can achieve because I’m willing to put in the work.

I want to leave you with something practical that if you adapt and you carry into your life it can radically transform everything that’s next for you.

And it’s this:

What you think becomes what you speak

What you speak becomes your action

Your actions become your reality

You have more power in your life than you’re giving yourself credit for. And until you make a declaration that you were going to allow yourself to be unlimited, you will not. This idea of mindset is everything starts with choosing to empower yourself with the belief that on a long enough timeline you can accomplish anything and that you can have the life that you want to have but...

there’s no Disney moment and no one’s coming to save you.

Change only happens when you make change happen.

I know that’s a lot of pressure and I know it’s unfair and I know that you wish, like me, that it wasn’t true but it is and when you acknowledge, accept, adapt, and take accountability for your life than that sentence of suffering can be a sentence of power.

Accept what you can control.

I have one simple ask of you if you’ve made it this far. I want you to take a piece of paper and a pen and I want you to write this down, and I want you to read this to yourself every day, and I want you to do that 1000 times a day until you convince yourself that it’s true.

Write this: "I am the kind of person who is kind to myself."

When you operate through a scope of kindness you will change everything in your life but that kindness has to start with you before you give it to the world. right now you’re saying things to yourself that if you said to another human being would get you punched in the face or even arrested. Think about that.

I believe that on a long enough timeline we all have the ability to change our narrative, to remove ourselves from the expectations of our ZIP Code, and to look at ourselves in the mirror with love, compassion, hope, trust, pride, and belief. but in order to cultivate those things you’re going to have to do incredibly difficult tasks and in doing these incredible difficult tasks you will discover what you are capable of and in that discovery you will choose to go even further than what you believe is possible today. But it all starts at step one. and trust me when I say that momentum is everything in life.

For some of us the hardest thing we will ever do is ask for help. As a trauma survivor I know how scary that can be to put your trust into someone else. But let me tell you this, when you rebuild and establish trust with other human beings you will discover that the world is not as dark as we’ve been led to believe it is.

I see greatness for you but you have to choose to see it first. And you have to trust the process, the guidance, the signs, your heart, and your vision of what you dream about at night. You can have everything that you want. I'm not saying it's east...I'm only saying it's possible.

There is no spoon.

Be Unbroken my friends,

@MichaelUnbroken

P.S. If you want to celebrate my birthday with me simply listen to an episode of The Think Unbroken Podcast. That would mean the world to me.

Thank you my being here. I love you."

["Complete the following:
Question: How could a cowboy ride into town on Friday, stay two days, and ride out on Wednesday?
A) His Horse is named Wednesday.  B) While in town, he stays in bed for 2 days.  C) Friday and Saturday are holidays. D) None of the Above.
Answer: The explicit premises of the question are as follows 1a.) Cowboy rides into town on Friday. 2a.) Cowboy stays in town for two days. 3a.) Cowboy rides out on Wednesday. The implicit assumptions of the question are as follows 1b.) Wednesday is the third day of the week. 2b.) Sunday is two days after Friday. Note that the implicit assumptions and explicit premises conflict. If the Cowboy rides into town on Friday (1a), stays in town for two days (2a), the premise that the cowboy rides out on Wednesday (3a) conflicts with the premise that Sunday is two days after Friday (2b). Note that if the cowboy’s horse is named Wednesday, this resolves the conflict as (3a) and (1b, 2b) no longer conflict. Thus A) is the correct answer.

that resonate with your beliefs.

["Take the following text

“The one at the Meads's house, where it's bigger inside than out; there's a European village just inside, with a cobblestone street and a Pied-Piper sort of man with curly hair, he can do things like juggle - I go up the back stairs [there aren't any in the real house] and then down the other side [since there's a second set, immediately] then down a short empty hallway that turns a corner, where I find a tiny room...a young woman with shoulder-length blonde hair in a pageboy is there, cooking at a stove that almost fills the room...she's nice to me. Now outside, I'm waiting for my aunt to pick me up - she arrives in a little round convertible and we go for a drive, not very far - we cross a little bridge over a creek, then double back and she drops me off at the house again. Inside (?) I sit with a couple of people, playing with a string of blue balloons.” 

Now count in the dream report the number of situations which correspond to one of the following 9 categories

“I. Condensation
Two or more objects or persons are fused or partly fused to make one object or person or person-like object. A partial fusion of separate objects may be expressed in the dream by a feeling of vagueness or uncertainty (See Freud, 1955, pp. 279-304.) Under condensation we included: (a) image fusion, (b) a simultaneous view of objects from inside and from outside, and (c) dissociation from the self, as when a dreamer reports observing himself in the dream.

II. Unlikely combinations or events 
Events are described that, while not impossible or completely illogical, leave one feeling that something about them is strange. Objects or persons are assembled out of parts that do not belong together in reality or a part is out of proportion compared to the share of the part in real life. Under unlikely combinations we included: (a) composite structures that occur in mythology or folklore, (b) inappropriate or anachronistic happenings, such as inappropriate dress, (c) events that are unlikely because of their size or scope, such as fires or floods involving more territory than such catastrophes usually involve, and (d) impossible combinations, for example, nonexistent or dead persons, animals that talk, lions in the basement of a house, a person flying without an airplane.

III. Fluid transformations
Included are: (a) objects or persons that appear or disappear suddenly, or are transformed into something else in front of the dreamer's eyes, and (b) sudden shifts in scene without a smoothing of transition through logical explanation.

IV. Visual representation
As many students of dreaming have noted, abstract relationships are usually represented in dreams visually (cf. Freud, 19SS,
pp. 339-349). Since this category should be scored conservatively, we offer the following subcategories as guides to scoring: (a) One person or object is literally exchanged for another; for example, "I used my sister's alarm clock instead of my own"; (b) spatial closeness is stressed or commented on by the dreamer, seeming to represent visually a closeness between two persons.

V. Symbolism
Since the basis of this scoring system is the coding of the manifest dream, rather than the interpretation of the dream with the help of associations, symbolism must be scored most conservatively. As Freud (1955, pp. 350-360) pointed out, even though the assumption that many symbols have a fixed meaning is often helpful, it is sometimes unjustified; and the basic method of dream interpretation involves use of the dreamer's associations. Therefore, we recommend the following rule: symbolism should be scored if a feature of the dream is overemphasized beyond its necessary role in the narrative. One should not score symbolism if the emphasis on the element is appropriate. In a narrative about hunting it is appropriate to find much discussion of guns; in such a case, we do not score symbolism, regardless of Freud's (1955, p. 356) remarks about the phallic significance of rifles. Example: We were traveling along the highway with a group of my friends. We were going to a convention or something. All of a sudden I had a great desire to have a glass of milk. We stopped for a rest, and asked the waitress for a glass of milk. She said they didn't have any. So I had a great desire for milk, and every place that I went to they just didn't have any (Scored as symbolism because the intensity of the dreamer's wish for milk is out of proportion to the circumstances of the dream; it isn't logically accounted for).

VI. Contradiction
This category should be scored when there is a defect in the dreamer's reasoning, or when his affect is inappropriate to the situation,
but not merely because something in the dream report is strange. Included are: (a) actions or feelings that are inappropriate or exaggerated; for example, the dreamer feels overworked in a store where there are no customers, and (b) illogical relations or explanations, for example, an assertion and denial side by side.

VII. Magic occurrences
Magical thoughts in dreams seem to represent, very directly, the hallucination of wish-fulfilling events. Subcategories are:
(a) verbalization to produce a magical effect, or with a mysterious meaning, (b) magical patterns (enigmas) or numbers with magical meaning, and (c) acts that produce magical effects, for example, acts that produce instant happiness or have a deus ex machina effect.

VIII. Inhibited movement
According to Freud (1955, p. 337), the sensation of the inhibition of a movement represents a conflict of will. Whatever its meaning, we consider it to be a primary-process mechanism, and score it as such.

IX. Taboo sexual and aggressive acts
Sexual and aggressive activity is not to be coded as indicating primary-process thinking if the activity fits logically
into the dream narrative, but only if it is the hallucination of a direct gratification without regard for context. Thus the report of a murder is not necessarily scored as primary process, since the actions producing the death involve delay and planning,
which are characteristics of secondary-process functioning, but the report that a person dropped dead, because one wished it, would be counted as primary process. Items included in this category are therefore something like those included in Category
VII, Magic occurrences.”

and provide numbers in brackets of how often the criteria of each of the 9 categories are met.
"]

Elf number 3 delivers presents to every third house: 3, 6, 9, 12, 15, ....

House 8 got 150 presents.
House 9 got 130 presents.

["Your archeologist friend found a scroll during her latest excavation, but unfortunately, the writing on the scroll is corrupted. She believes that the writing on the scroll may be a duplicate of an existing text. You offer to help her by writing a computer program that compares strings and tries to align them according to their similarities. You ask her for a scoring system for character comparison, and she gives you the following function:

alignment score = (# of matching characters * match score)  - (# of gaps * gap score) - (# of mismatching characters * mismatch score)
For example, if the readable sequence on the scroll is "CC", the possible match string is "CD", the match score is 4, the gap score is 1, and the mismatch score is 2, then the possible alignments between the strings and their scores are as follows:

(The character "_" denotes a gap in the first string, "." denotes a gap in the second string, and "!" denotes a mismatch.)

CC__
..CD
aligned:
..__ => alignment does not have any matches or mismatches, only gaps
gap, gap, gap, gap => (0 * 4)-(4 * 1)- (0 * 2) = 0 - 4 - 0 = -4

CC_
.CD
aligned:
.C_  => alignment has two gaps, one match, no mismatch
gap, match, gap => (1 * 4) - (2 * 1) - (0 * 2) = 4 - 2 - 0 = 2

CC
CD
aligned:
C!   => alignment has one match and one mismatch
match, mismatch => (1 * 4) - (0 * 1) - (1 * 2) = 4 - 0 - 2 = 2
_CC
CD. 
aligned:
_!.  => alignment has one mismatch and two gaps
gap, mismatch, gap => (0 * 4) - (2 * 1) - (1 * 2) = 0 - 2 - 2 = -4

__CC
CD..
aligned:
__.. => alignment does not have any matches or mismatches, only gaps
gap, gap, gap, gap => (0 * 4) - (4 * 1) - (0 * 2) = 0 - 4 - 0 = -4



Problem 

In this exam, you are asked to compare the two given sequences and find one possible alignment with the highest match score with two different approaches by completing the recursive_alignment() defined below. 


int recursive_alignment(std::string sequence_A, std::string sequence_B, int gap, int mismatch, int match, std::string &possible_alignment, int call_count);


You should return the highest alignment score of the two sequences as the return value for both functions. The arguments of the function are defined as follows with their limits:

sequence_A and sequence_B are strings to be compared, with lengths <= 10000
gap is the integer penalty point for leaving a gap in the alignment, where 0 <= gap <= 10
mismatch is the integer penalty point for a mismatch in the alignment, where 0 <= mismatch <= 10
match is the integer point for a successful match in the alignment, where 0 <= match <= 10
possible_alignment is a string that includes one of the possible alignments for two sequences with the highest alignment score, where the character "_" denotes a gap in sequence_A, "." denotes a gap in sequence_B, and "!" denotes a mismatch.
call_count is an integer used to keep track of the number of recursive calls. 

Let F(i,j) denote the best alignment score when looking at index i of sequence_A and index j of sequence_B. Then, the recurrence relation of this problem can be defined as follows:

F(i,j) = max(F(i-1, j-1) + c(i,j),
             F(i-1, j) - gap,
             F(i, j-1) - gap)
where c(i,j) stands for the comparison between the characters sequence_A[i] and sequence_B[j], and returns match or -mismatch accordingly.

["Revise my introduction based on my professor's feedback
Overall Feedback
One introduction paragraph that provides a brief overview of the issue you have chosen and ends in your thesis statement. 

Here is an example of an introductory paragraph for an argument on book bans:

Joseph Heller once said “He knew everything about literature, except how to enjoy it” (“The Top 12”). There is a current epidemic in the United States that is affecting schools across the country: book bans. Religious groups, politicians, and parents are constantly attacking pieces of classic literature or other academic works and attempting to have them removed from the curriculum. This is often because individuals or groups believe a piece of literature carries a message or theme that conflicts with their own personal beliefs, or because the theme of the book is misunderstood. Schools should not ban any literature in the curriculum or libraries because this practice suggests that only some ideas or experiences are worthy of discussion, eliminates narratives on difficult subjects that students can relate to, and reinforces a singular way of thinking.

Your thesis statement should be located at the end of your introduction; it should state your argument, ideally using “should” or “should not” and list your three key supporting points. For example: Schools should not ban any literature from the curriculum or libraries because this practice suggests that only some ideas or experiences are worthy of discussion, eliminates narratives on difficult subjects students can relate to, and reinforces a singular way of thinking.
In the dynamic landscape of small business financial management, a critical debate emerges, posing the question of whether small enterprises should prioritize outsourcing accounting services or invest in computer programs.
As an accounting major, I bring a unique perspective to this ongoing discussion, allowing for a nuanced exploration of the intricate decisions faced by small businesses rooted in the nuances of the accounting field. This analysis caters to a diverse audience, ranging from those unfamiliar with outsourcing advantages to individuals well-versed in financial and technological solutions.
Navigating this terrain, my thesis is clear: Small businesses should prioritize outsourcing accounting services over investing in computer programs to leverage financial expertise, enhance operational focus, and capitalize on cost-effectiveness. This assertion forms the foundation of the essay, guiding the comprehensive analysis that follows and providing a clear direction for understanding the strategic advantages of outsourcing in the realm of small business financial management.
With a tailored approach, the essay aims to address concerns, counter skepticism, and offer valuable insights to guide small businesses in their critical financial management decisions. The purpose of this paper is to conduct a comprehensive analysis of whether small businesses should prioritize outsourcing accounting services over investing in computer programs. By addressing skepticism through clear arguments, real-world examples, and a balanced discussion, this essay navigates concerns about data security, loss of control, and potential reductions in service quality.
","Change my Body paragraph based on my professor's feedback
You should have 4-5 body paragraphs: one for each of the three key supporting points and one to two paragraphs to cover one or two opposing viewpoints. Focus on fully developing each idea in a single paragraph so the information is not fragmented. 

For each key point paragraph, you should begin by stating the topic of the paragraph (the key point that will be addressed). Explain that point briefly if needed and then add the evidence from your sources to support your claim. This should be done using a brief paraphrase. Always follow source evidence with your own analysis of what the information means, how it supports the paragraph's point, and how it supports your overall argument. You may repeat the evidence/analysis pattern several times in a single paragraph. These are the elements of a TEA paragraph.

Here is an example of a developed, argumentative paragraph where I have highlighted the source information in bold text and my own analysis of that information (original thought) in italics. This shows you how brief source information should be when incorporated into a paragraph and how extensive your analysis of that information should be:

Book bans eliminate narratives on difficult subjects that many students are able to relate to. These issues may include anything from divorce and abuse, to racism and homophobia. Heart of Darkness, by Joseph Conrad, is often misinterpreted as a racist novel rather than a novel that brings forth the horrors that occurred during colonization in the Congo (Mastropierro and Conklin 25). Conrad himself is often called racist for writing the novel because many people read or hear about a single scene or specific language out of context and do not realize or understand the overall theme of the book. This particular book brings forward the issue of racism that can be a difficult subject to discuss, even though it is so important. Conrad paints a picture of his own journey through the Congo and shows the readers the truth of what he saw: The British were the true “savages” in Africa, not the Africans as claimed. To Kill a Mockingbird is another book that is often targeted even though it creates discussions about racism, civil rights, and issues with the legal system. In the book, a main story line is an innocent black man, Tom, being accused of raping a white woman. The reader knows that Tom is innocent from the start, so it is easy for them to see and understand the racism that Tom faces, especially when he is convicted by an all-white jury and sentenced to death. This story line is one that makes many people uncomfortable, and out-of-context, some mistakenly believe that the book itself is racist because of Tom’s fate (Zorthian 1). However, Tom is the character that readers connect and fall in love with, so it hits students hard when they learn of his fate. Students feel for Tom. Those students who have suffered the effects of racism connect with Tom, and those who have never experienced it themselves begin to feel what it is like through their own connection with the character. This connection is what makes students want to talk about these topics and opens narratives on the issues Tom faced. Without these books, students would lose that connection to the topic and essentially miss out on, not only a chance to learn, but a chance to connect and to feel.

For the opposing viewpoint paragraph, begin by identifying the opposing point of view and provide an explanation. Why does the opposition think that way? Use source evidence to back up those claims. Then, use the rest of the paragraph to illustrate why that point of view is flawed or completely incorrect. Use cited source information to back up your claims. This refutation should take up the bulk of the paragraph.
II. Supporting Argument
A.	Specialized Financial Expertise:
The research conducted by Walker, Johnson, and Fleischman (2018) investigates the dimensions of service quality in management accounting (MA) and offers valuable insights for small businesses considering outsourcing accounting services or investing in computer programs. The study identifies three critical dimensions of service quality: functional, technical, and image (Walker, Johnson, & Fleischman, 2018). Notably, survey participants placed the greatest emphasis on the technical quality of information and reports, indicating that users prioritize the expertise and reliability of accounting information. This finding suggests that for small businesses, outsourcing accounting services to specialized professionals could be advantageous, as it ensures high-quality technical outputs. While computer programs may address certain aspects of functional quality, they may fall short in delivering the nuanced technical expertise required in MA. The research underscores the importance of understanding customer perceptions and tailoring services, accordingly, emphasizing that the complex and organization-specific nature of MA service quality should guide strategic decisions for small businesses (Walker et al., 2018).
B.	Operational Efficiency and Focus:
Lanz (2013) highlights the significant impact of technology on the accounting profession and emphasizes the need for CPAs to understand and leverage relevant technology to deliver superior services. In the context of small and midsized businesses (SMBs), the article underscores the changing face of business technology, particularly with the rise of cloud computing. Lanz suggests that SMBs can benefit from outsourcing certain technological functions to vendors, allowing them to focus on evaluating and selecting vendors to achieve business objectives rather than managing detailed technology parameters. This shift provides opportunities for CPAs to assist SMBs in navigating the implementation of new technological skills required for success in a technology-dependent world. The article identifies key IT risks, such as availability, access, accuracy, and agility, and emphasizes how CPAs can help SMBs address these risks, providing guidance on issues like business continuity planning, information security, data accuracy, and managing change. The insights from Lanz's article support the argument that outsourcing accounting services, especially in the context of addressing technological challenges, can be advantageous for SMBs over solely investing in computer programs.
C.	Cost-Effectiveness and Flexibility:
The study by Shields and Shelleman (2016) sheds light on the significance of management accounting systems (MAS) in micro-SMEs (small and medium-sized enterprises), providing empirical evidence on their use and outcomes. The research, based on a sample of 55 micro-SMEs, reveals that these businesses employ various MAS elements, including the computation of product/service profitability, comparisons of actual to budgeted performance, and assessment of customer profitability. Importantly, the study establishes a positive correlation between more frequent use of MAS, particularly in computing product or service profitability and assessing customer profitability, and higher return on investment (ROI). The findings underscore the relevance of MAS in enhancing decision-making processes for micro-SMEs, offering insights into the relative importance of management accounting information for these businesses. This empirical evidence supports the argument that investing in effective management accounting practices positively impacts financial performance.

III. Addressing and Refuting Opposing Viewpoints
1.	Concerns about Data Security:
One common objection to outsourcing is the concern about data security. Skeptics argue that handing over sensitive financial information to external service providers exposes businesses to potential risks. However, this concern can be effectively mitigated through stringent contractual agreements, encryption technologies, and thorough vetting of outsourcing partners. Reputable outsourcing firms invest heavily in security measures, often surpassing the capabilities of individual small businesses.
2.	Loss of Control Over Financial Processes:
Another argument against outsourcing revolves around the fear of losing control over financial processes. Some business owners prefer in-house management to maintain direct oversight. However, modern outsourcing arrangements allow for transparent communication, regular updates, and collaboration. This not only ensures a level of control but also leverages the expertise of professionals who specialize in financial management, ultimately enhancing the overall financial health of the business.
3.	Potential Reductions in Service Quality:
Critics often express concerns about potential reductions in service quality when outsourcing. However, careful selection of reputable outsourcing partners with a proven track record can mitigate these worries.
Source: "Management Accounting Service Quality: What IS Most Important to Your Customers" by Walker, Johnson, and Fleischman.
Emphasizing that outsourcing, when executed strategically, can enhance service quality by providing access to specialized expertise.
In summary, systematically refuting these opposing viewpoints strengthens the argument for outsourcing. By addressing concerns about data security, loss of control, and reductions in service quality with evidence-backed counterarguments, the essay provides a clear and persuasive case for prioritizing outsourcing in small business financial management.

I. Introduction
In the ever-evolving world of small business financial management, a pressing debate has emerged, questioning whether small enterprises should prioritize outsourcing accounting services or invest in computer programs. This complex issue affects a diverse audience, from those unfamiliar with the benefits of outsourcing to individuals well-versed in financial and technological solutions. As an accounting major, my unique perspective allows for a nuanced exploration of the intricate decisions faced by small businesses, rooted in the understanding of the accounting field.
The purpose of this paper is to provide a comprehensive analysis of whether small businesses should prioritize outsourcing accounting services over investing in computer programs, addressing concerns such as data security, loss of control, and potential reductions in service quality. Navigating this terrain, my thesis statement is clear: Small businesses should prioritize outsourcing accounting services over investing in computer programs because it allows them to leverage financial expertise, enhance operational focus, and capitalize on cost-effectiveness. This argument forms the foundation of the essay, offering valuable insights to guide small businesses in their critical financial management decisions while addressing skepticism through clear arguments and real-world examples.
This section aims to provide a comprehensive analysis showcasing the understanding of the financial management challenges faced by small businesses.




II. Supporting Argument
A. Specialized Financial Expertise:
One significant advantage of outsourcing accounting services for small businesses is the access to specialized financial expertise. Walker, Johnson, and Fleischman (2018) conducted research investigating the dimensions of service quality in management accounting (MA), which offers valuable insights for small businesses considering outsourcing accounting services or investing in computer programs. The study identifies three critical dimensions of service quality: functional, technical, and image (Walker et al., 2018). Notably, survey participants placed the greatest emphasis on the technical quality of information and reports, indicating that users prioritize the expertise and reliability of accounting information. This finding suggests that for small businesses, outsourcing accounting services to specialized professionals could be advantageous, as it ensures high-quality technical outputs. While computer programs may address certain aspects of functional quality, they may fall short in delivering the nuanced technical expertise required in MA. The research underscores the importance of understanding customer perceptions and tailoring services accordingly, emphasizing that the complex and organization-specific nature of MA service quality should guide strategic decisions for small businesses (Walker et al., 2018).
B. Operational Efficiency and Focus:
Another benefit of outsourcing accounting services is the potential for increased operational efficiency and focus. Lanz (2013) highlights the significant impact of technology on the accounting profession and emphasizes the need for CPAs to understand and leverage relevant technology to deliver superior services. In the context of small and midsized businesses (SMBs), the article underscores the changing face of business technology, particularly with the rise of cloud computing. Lanz suggests that SMBs can benefit from outsourcing certain technological functions to vendors, allowing them to focus on evaluating and selecting vendors to achieve business objectives rather than managing detailed technology parameters. This shift provides opportunities for CPAs to assist SMBs in navigating the implementation of new technological skills required for success in a technology-dependent world. The article identifies key IT risks, such as availability, access, accuracy, and agility, and emphasizes how CPAs can help SMBs address these risks, providing guidance on issues like business continuity planning, information security, data accuracy, and managing change. The insights from Lanz's article support the argument that outsourcing accounting services, especially in the context of addressing technological challenges, can be advantageous for SMBs over solely investing in computer programs.
C. Cost-Effectiveness and Flexibility:
Outsourcing accounting services can contribute to cost-effectiveness and flexibility for small businesses. Shields and Shelleman (2016) conducted a study on the significance of management accounting systems (MAS) in micro-SMEs (small and medium-sized enterprises), providing empirical evidence on their use and outcomes. The research, based on a sample of 55 micro-SMEs, reveals that these businesses employ various MAS elements, including the computation of product/service profitability, comparisons of actual to budgeted performance, and assessment of customer profitability. Importantly, the study establishes a positive correlation between more frequent use of MAS, particularly in computing product or service profitability and assessing customer profitability, and higher return on investment (ROI). The findings underscore the relevance of MAS in enhancing decision-making processes for micro-SMEs, offering insights into the relative importance of management accounting information for these businesses. This empirical evidence supports the argument that investing in effective management accounting practices positively impacts financial performance.
By outsourcing accounting services, small businesses can achieve cost savings by avoiding the need to hire and train in-house accounting staff, as well as reducing overhead costs associated with office space and equipment. Additionally, outsourcing allows small businesses to access a wider pool of accounting expertise and experience, which can lead to more accurate and efficient financial reporting and decision-making. Furthermore, outsourcing provides flexibility for small businesses, as they can scale up or down the level of accounting services required based on their changing needs and financial situation. In contrast, investing in computer programs may entail significant upfront costs and require ongoing maintenance, updates, and staff training, which can be both time-consuming and expensive. Overall, outsourcing accounting services can offer cost-effectiveness and flexibility for small businesses, supporting the argument that they should prioritize outsourcing over investing in computer programs.

III. Addressing and Refuting Opposing Viewpoints
1.	Concerns about Data Security:
One common objection to outsourcing accounting services is the concern about data security. Skeptics argue that handing over sensitive financial information to external service providers exposes businesses to potential risks. However, this concern can be effectively mitigated through stringent contractual agreements, encryption technologies, and thorough vetting of outsourcing partners. Reputable outsourcing firms invest heavily in security measures, often surpassing the capabilities of individual small businesses. By implementing these safeguards, small businesses can ensure the protection of their sensitive financial data while still benefiting from the expertise and cost-effectiveness provided by outsourcing.
2.	Loss of Control Over Financial Processes:
Another argument against outsourcing revolves around the fear of losing control over financial processes. Some business owners prefer in-house management to maintain direct oversight. However, modern outsourcing arrangements allow for transparent communication, regular updates, and collaboration. This not only ensures a level of control but also leverages the expertise of professionals who specialize in financial management, ultimately enhancing the overall financial health of the business. By carefully selecting outsourcing partners and maintaining open lines of communication, small businesses can maintain control over their financial processes while still benefiting from the advantages of outsourcing.
3.	Potential Reductions in Service Quality:
Critics often express concerns about potential reductions in service quality when outsourcing accounting services. However, careful selection of reputable outsourcing partners with a proven track record can mitigate these worries. By choosing experienced and skilled professionals, small businesses can ensure that their financial management needs are met with the highest level of service quality. This, in turn, can lead to more accurate and timely financial reporting and decision-making, further supporting the argument for prioritizing outsourcing in small business financial management.

In summary, systematically refuting these opposing viewpoints strengthens the argument for outsourcing accounting services. By addressing concerns about data security, loss of control, and reductions in service quality with evidence-backed counterarguments, the essay provides a clear and persuasive case for prioritizing outsourcing in small business financial management.
